    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.24.3-4_0001"/>
                
                <note type="curatorial">Neihardt Collection</note>
                <fw type="curatorial">3</fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        643 <hi rend="caps">N.</hi> 10th Street
                        East St. Louis, Illinois
                        February 19, 1956
                    </dateline>
                    
                    <address>
                        <addrLine>Mr. John <hi rend="caps">G.</hi> Neihardt</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>English Department</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>University Of Missouri</addrLine>
                        <addrLine>Columbia, Missouri</addrLine>
                    </address>
                  
                <salute>Dear Mr. Neihardt:</salute></opener>          <p>Your <hi rend="caps">T-V</hi> poetry program this mo<del>t</del><add>r</add>ning is the best thing I have ever seen over the "air"; in this new medium of communication. Only, wh<del>t</del><add>y</add> didn't you read some of your verse ? Of all your poems , I think I like the one best that ends,"And feels the Master <del/><add>M</add>elody and snaps!" <add>*</add></p>
                
                <p>As you might have guessed, one reason your poetry program impressed me is because I too am a poet. At least, I am something of an oddity in poets, since I am a civil engineer who writes. I got my <hi rend="caps">B.S.</hi> in Civil Engineering from the University Of Missouri in 1927. I have written poetry since my junior year at college. In 1930, I printed all the verses I had previously published in newspaper open columns, in the form of a mimeographed book. I called this, "I Want To Live".</p>
                
                <p>Here is a poem I was lucky enough to get in <hi rend="caps">F.H.</hi> Collier's "Echoes Of The Street" column in the <hi rend="underline">Globe-<add>D</add>emocrat</hi> during the 1930's. This was about the Smog problem in St. Louis and other cities.</p>
                <lg>
                <l><hi rend="caps">BLACK SNOW</hi></l>
                
                <l>No longer, thru the pensive night,</l>
                <l>Fall flakes of snow, entirely white,</l>
                <l>But thru the atmosphere descends,</l>
                <l>This sombre mass that none befriends,--</l>
                <l>A sort of black, advesive<sic>adhesive</sic> snow</l>
                <l>Paints sticky shadows, here below.</l>
                </lg>
                <milestone unit="section"/><ab>........</ab>
                
                <p>The University Of MIssouri's<sic>Missouri's</sic> love for poets is not a new one. Stratton Deluth Brooks, President when I graduated, brought Edw<del>a</del>in Markham there in 1927 to deliver the com<add>m</add>encement address. He used this quatrain to illustrate his talk:
                
                <add><note type="authorial">(His address was an apology for those of us who only do the "little things".</note></add></p>
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.24.3-4_0002"/>
                
                    <fw type="curatorial">4</fw>
                    
                    <fw type="authorial">-2-</fw>
                <lg>
                <l><hi rend="caps">THE FATHER'S BUSINESS</hi></l>
                    
                <l>Who puts back into place a fallen bar,</l>
                <l>Or flings a stone from a traveled road;</l>
                <l>His feet are moving towards a central star,</l>
                <l>His name is whispered in the God's Abode.</l>
                
                <l>By Edwin Markham</l></lg>
                <milestone unit="section"/><ab>:::::::</ab>
                <p>I sure hope you can continue to get poetry porgram<add>s</add> like the one I saw today, on the Television and/or Radio.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Respectfully Yours,</salute>
                    <signed>Vernus Noble Pyle</signed>
                    <signed>Vernus Noble Pyle</signed>
                </closer>
                
                <postscript>
                    <opener><hi rend="underline"><hi rend="caps">P.S.</hi></hi></opener> <p>All your poets today were good. <list><item>1 The woman who knew children so well was good.</item> <item>2 I could feel the intensity of the Blind Poet's creation.</item> <item>3 The first poet has lots of originality.</item></list></p> <closer><signed>VNP</signed></closer>
                </postscript>
                
                <postscript>
                    <opener><hi rend="caps">P.P.S.</hi></opener> <p>* I went down to the St. Louis library and looked up this verse. I was afraid my memory had tricked me and this was by some author other than yourself. Now I know it was yours&#8212; "Let Me <unclear>Live</unclear> Out My Years." We used to recite this at the <hi rend="caps">BLUE LANTERN INN</hi>, <unclear/>, St. Louis attempt at a <unclear>greenwich</unclear> <unclear/></p>
                    </postscript>
                
                <note type="authorial" place="right_margin">How long have you lived in Columbia? I was there for many years <unclear reason="missing"/></note>
                
            </div1>
